<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#D0BC90">Originally posted by lynn on 01-08-2003 03:33 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL"> [IMG]http://www.larian.com/Site/artwork/rpgsurprise.gif"[/IMG] 

Both [URL=http://www.rpgdot.com/index.php?hsaction=10053&ID=483]RPGDot's[/URL] readership and editors awarded Divine Divinity the [b]RPG Surprise of the Year 2002 award[/b]. Here's some of their conclusion

[i]"Many people expressed disappointment this year over over-hyped games that did not deliver on what the developers or publishers promised. As an virtual unknown, Divine Divinity was certainly free of that burden. The great thing about the game is that it did deliver what the developers said it would. This probably explains everyone's surprise."[/i]

* * *

[URL=http://www.rpgcodex.com/content.php?id=27]RPGCodex[/URL] had 4 of their editors name their [b]Must-Play CRPG of 2002[/b]. Two of them named Divine Divinity. Here's what both of them had to say:

[i]"My choice for Divine Divinity as one of my top picks this year is quite simply based on the fact that I played it, and that I quite liked it. What interested me most about the game was the interactivity. Simply put, you can do a lot of things in it that most RPG developers these days don't even consider to implement. To top it off, that's not even the gist of why I like Divine Divinity. If I were you, I'd put Divine Divinity on my holiday list."[/i]

[i]"While some will cringe at the thought of *another* isometric high-fantasy CRPG, this game actually has a lot more to offer in the fun-factor department than most of its rivals."[/i]

* * *

[URL=http://www.gameaxis.com/articles/view.gax?id=69&PHPSESSID=c6dd212792180bde18b35122c8444f3b"]GameAxis[/URL] reviewed Divine Divinity and came to the conclusion that they too liked it a lot. [b]Their score: 93%[/b]. Here's an excerpt from the review:

[i]"Divine Divinity is one of the best RPG's I have ever came across. To be frank, I am someone very particular about story plots when it comes to games, and I placed more emphasis on a story rather than, say, graphics. This game has never failed to absorb me into its world whenever I play, and the excellent music has not once failed to heighten my emotions. Be it tension, excitement or even a sense of urgency. I will highly recommend this game to any RPG lovers, or anyone who is just looking for something fun to play."[/i]

* * *

And finally, [URL=http://www.rpgfan.com/reviews/divinedivinity/Divine_Divinity.html] RPGFan[/URL] reviewed Divine Divinity too and rated it [b]96%[/b].

[i]"Everyone plays games differently, and it is refreshing to come across a game that knows that. And while it is difficult to maintain a level of professionalism while saying such things as "Oh my God! Get this game!" I am afraid I will miss making my point if I do not. So, in closing: Oh my God! Get this game! Divine Divinity will undoubtedly be proudly shown on your shelves for a great length of time (even if its name is not)."[/i]

------------------
Larian Studios Member
------------------
[i]They say don't judge a book by its cover, and in equal measure don't judge a game by its name[/i]</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
